<article id="post-2261" class="hentry post publish post-1 odd author-admin format-standard category-author-interview-2 category-giveaway category-indieself-pub-author-event post_tag-author-interview post_tag-giveaway-2 post_tag-indieself-pub-event post_tag-lindsay-buroker">

	
		
		<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="post-title entry-title"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://novelideareviews.com/author-interview-giveaway-lindsay-buroker/">Author Interview + Giveaway: Lindsay Buroker</a></h1>			<div class="byline">Published by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" rel="author" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://novelideareviews.com/author/admin/" title="Paola">Paola</a></span> on <abbr class="published" title="Friday, June 28th, 2013, 10:00 am">June 28, 2013</abbr>  | <a class="comments-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://novelideareviews.com/author-interview-giveaway-lindsay-buroker/#comments" title="Comment on Author Interview + Giveaway: Lindsay Buroker">14 Responses</a> </div>		</header><!-- .entry-header -->
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com']);" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter" alt="indieeventbanner" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/indieeventbanner.png" width="416" height="70"/></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: justify;">Today I have <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://lindsayburoker.com/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://lindsayburoker.com']);" target="_blank"><strong>Lindsay Buroker</strong></a> on the blog for a chat about possible assassin tendencies, bringing <em>Emperor&#8217;s Edge</em> to an end (or not??), and which of her characters she&#8217;d rather not bunk with!</h4>
<h4 style="text-align: justify;">I&#8217;m thrilled to feature Lindsay here, since she happens to be one of my favorite self-published authors and I&#8217;ve been a huge fan of <em>Emperor&#8217;s Edge</em> since reading <a title="The Emperor’s Edge" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://novelideareviews.com/the-emperors-edge/" target="_blank">the first book</a> way back in 2011. If you haven&#8217;t met Amaranthe, Sicarius and the gang, that first installment is <strong>free</strong> for Kindle, Nook, and other eBook retailers&#8230; OR you can enter today&#8217;s <strong>giveaway</strong> for <strong>an eBook copy of the omnibus edition containing books 1-3</strong>! (<em>The Emperor&#8217;s Edge, Dark Currents, Deadly Games</em>) And a big thank you to Lindsay for taking time to do this interview while working hard on the second half of <em>Forged In Blood</em>!</h4>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">An Interview with Lindsay Buroker</span></h3>
<p><strong>- I have to ask&#8230; how does it feel to be writing the final installment of EE? You&#8217;ve come such a long way with your characters and the books. </strong></p>
<p>I&#8217;m thinking of it as the end of a story arc and a chance to work on something else for a while. I have a feeling I&#8217;ll come back to the characters at some point, so it doesn&#8217;t really feel like the final installment. I&#8217;ll just send them off on some new adventure in the future, though I&#8217;m not sure if that will involve the whole team or just a couple of the characters. We&#8217;ll see what people ask for!</p>
<p><span id="more-2261"></span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>- How much of your own personality found its way into your characters? (Read: are you actually possessed of Sicarius-level assassin skills?? Wait, maybe don&#8217;t tell us if that&#8217;s true&#8230;)</strong></p>
<p>Hm, I once did the Myers-Briggs personality type test on the major characters. Perhaps I shouldn&#8217;t mention that Sicarius and I were very similar?</p>
<p>As for assassin skills and knives, nope, I can&#8217;t do any of the things he does. I don&#8217;t share a lot of common hobbies with anyone on the team. Don&#8217;t tell Maldynado, but I don&#8217;t even like to shop. The only hat I own is to keep the sun out of my eyes while I play tennis.</p>
<p>It is possible that some of my, ah, unique brand of humor is reflected in the team&#8217;s dialogue though.</p>
<p><strong>- Which of the EE gang would you get along with best? Least?</strong></p>
<p>Amaranthe would keep trying to straighten my clothes and trim my hair, so I don&#8217;t know about her&#8230; I&#8217;m sure I&#8217;d get along well with Maldynado, because&#8230; really, who doesn&#8217;t?</p>
<p>Sicarius would be a tad unnerving, so I&#8217;d pass on spending time with him. Especially if he knows I&#8217;m the one who&#8217;s put him through all these torturous events in his life&#8230;</p>
<p><strong>- When you started writing EE, did you already have the entire story and outcome planned, or did you approach it one book at a time?</strong></p>
<p>Hahaha. Erm. No. ;)</p>
<p>I actually thought these guys would go on to have adventures for years without much changing, but the Forge arc took on a mind of its own, and Amaranthe and Sicarius wanted to move things along so they could finally&#8230; go on a vacation. Together.</p>
<p>In other words, I&#8217;ve been winging it!</p>
<p><strong>- Have any of your characters surprised you in terms of their development and/or reception by fans?</strong></p>
<p>I&#8217;ve been a little surprised by how popular Sicarius has become. He gets a lot of mail from concerned fans who want a happy ending for him. When I first trotted his character out, he was in charge of the group (Amaranthe didn&#8217;t exist yet in my mind then), and he didn&#8217;t get much love from my critique partners. I think bringing in Amaranthe and putting her in charge of the group made for an interesting dynamic, and, as Basilard has pointed out, she&#8217;s humanizing him a bit.</p>
<p>I am, of course, shocked that Maldynado doesn&#8217;t get more fan mail from the ladies. He&#8217;s just so&#8230; statue-worthy. (He might have made me write that.)</p>
<p><strong>- Do you have any favorite reads in the steampunk genre that you could recommend?</strong></p>
<p>I hate to admit it, but I haven&#8217;t read a lot in the genre and haven&#8217;t managed to finish many of the books I have picked up. I&#8217;ve found it a bit like science fiction in that it&#8217;s sometimes so much about the world building and the gadgets that you struggle to find characters you care about. I did like Scott Westerfeld&#8217;s <em>Leviathan</em> books enough to finish the series. The world-building was cool, but not overwhelming. One of the nice things about YA fiction is that it tends to move along well without getting bogged down in excessive details!</p>
<p>If any of your readers would like to suggest some authors for me to try, I&#8217;d be all ears. :)</p>
<p><strong>- Any advice for aspiring writers out there??</strong></p>
<p>With self-publishing all the rate, it&#8217;s easy to publish now, but my advice would be not to rush anything. A lot of writers finish their first book and want to put it out there, but most experienced authors will tell you that their first book (or three) sucked. As with anything, it takes practice, and you&#8217;ll learn faster by getting feedback and advice from peers and mentors. You can take writing classes, join critique groups, go to seminars, read books on the craft, etc. Just be prepared to do these things if you hope to make a career out of writing.</p>
<p>Even if you&#8217;re planning to self-publish, I think it&#8217;s a good idea to sell a few things (i.e. short stories) as a litmus test. If your work is polished enough that editors want to buy it, then you have a better shot at finding readers out there who will appreciate your stories.</p>
<p><strong>- Thank you so much!! I&#8217;m ending this now so I won&#8217;t interrupt your writing :D</strong></p>
<p>Thanks for inviting me to chat, Paola!</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Giveaway!</span></h3>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">June 28, 2013 &#8211; July 14, 2013</h3>
<h4 style="text-align: center;">Enter for a chance to win an omnibus edition of the first three books in the <em>Emperor&#8217;s Edge</em> series! (eBook format) This edition includes:</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Book I</strong>: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10031259-the-emperor-s-edge" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com']);" target="_blank"><em>The Emperor&#8217;s Edge</em></a></li>
<li><strong>Book II</strong>: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11672438-dark-currents" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com']);" target="_blank"><em>Dark Currents</em></a></li>
<li><strong>Book III</strong>: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13044650-deadly-games" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130702043700/http://www.goodreads.com']);" target="_blank"><em>Deadly Games</em></a></li>
</ul>
